Do you have a black box in your car?
While American road designers are trying to find money to repair a crumbling highway system, many are beginning to see the solution in a small black box carefully mounted on your car’s dashboard.
These devices, which track every mile a driver travels and transmit this information to officials, are at the heart of a controversial attempt to modernize America’s outdated highway financing system undertaken by Washington and the state planning authorities.
The usually boring arena of highway planning has unexpectedly sparked intense debate and colourful alliances.
Libertarians have joined environmental groups in lobbying to give the government the right to use small boxes to track how many miles you’re riding and even where you’re riding them – and then use that information to make tax bills.
Drinking tea in shock.
The American Civil Liberties Union is also deeply concerned and raises a number of privacy issues.
And although Congress can’t agree yet whether to continue or not, several states are not going to wait.
They are thinking about how in the next decade we can move to a system where drivers pay for every mile of road they drive.
Thousands of drivers have already tested these black boxes, some of which have a satellite tracking function.
This is really necessary for our country.
“It’s not a matter that we might have the right to choose,” said Hassan Ichrata, executive director of the Southern California Association of Governments, which is preparing plans to start tracking the state’s miles every California driver runs by 2025.
There will be changes in the way we pay these taxes.
The technology for this already exists.
The need for this is aggravated by the lack of funding from the Government’s Highway Construction Fund, funded by taxes that Americans pay on gasoline.
Americans no longer buy as much gasoline as before.
Cars travel more than a mile per gallon.
The federal tax, 18.4 cents per gallon, has not increased for 20 years.
Politicians do not want to raise the tax even one cent at high gas prices.
“The gasoline tax is simply impossible to save,” said Lee Manic, a transport policy expert at the University of Minnesota.
In his state, 500 tracking devices have recently been installed on cars to test a false payment system.
“It will be the best alternative in the long term,” he said.
Zanuod calls this a false user fee.
It is not surprising that this idea attracts urban liberals, as taxes will be able to change the nature of travel to reduce road congestion and greenhouse gas emissions, for example.
Planning authorities in California are overseeing this system as they develop strategies to meet the targets set by the state’s ambitious global warming laws.
However, House member Bill Schuster (Republican, Pennsylvania), chairman of the House Transportation Committee, said he also sees this system as the most viable long-term alternative.
Free market supporters at Reason are also delighted to have drivers pay for every mile.
“It’s not just a tax that will go into a black hole,” said Adrian Moore, Reason’s vice president for political affairs.
People pay directly for what they get.
This movement is also supported by two former U.S. transport ministers, who in 2011 urged Congress to move towards pardon.
Last year, the U.S. Senate approved a $90 million pilot project involving about 10,000 vehicles.
However, the House of Representatives rejected the proposal due to concerns from rural lawmakers representing voters who often have to travel many miles in their daily lives to get to work or the city.
Several states and cities, however, go this path on their own.
The biggest enthusiasm is shown in Oregon, where 5,000 drivers are attracted to participate in the country’s largest experiment.
These drivers will soon pay the state for miles of distance instead of gasoline taxes.
The pilot project in Nevada has already been completed.
It is being considered in New York.
Illinois will test it on a limited basis with the participation of trucks.
And the I-95 coalition, which comprises the transport departments of 17 eastern coastal states (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia, and Florida), is exploring how they can implement these changes.
This concept has not received universal recognition.
In Nevada, where about 50 volunteer cars were recently equipped with these devices, drivers were concerned that the government could track their every step.
“The concerns about the big brother and the like are a big problem,” said Alauddin Khan, head of strategy and efficiency management at the Nevada Department of Transportation.
It was not what people wanted.
As the tests were underway, the U.S. Civil Liberties Union’s Nevada branch warned on its website: “It will be easy to turn these devices into full-scale surveillance devices.”
There is no need to create a huge, massive technological infrastructure that will inevitably expand to keep records of individual citizens’ daily movements.
Nevada is one of a few states where it is difficult to find inexpensive technology that would allow the state authorities to keep records of the miles travelled by the car, but without information about place and time.
If you can do that, Khan said, society will feel more calm.
The search for this technology has led some state agencies to a small young company in California called True Mileage.
Initially, the company did not contribute to the collection of state taxes.
She sought to enter the developing market of type of car insurance, where drivers pay on the basis of distance.
But the devices she’s testing are attracting road designers because they don’t use GPS and provide a limited amount of information periodically loaded with a modem.
“People will be more likely to do this if you don’t track their speed or their location,” said Ryan Morrison, executive director of True Mileage.
There were several major mistakes in some of these state pilot programs.
There are far less expensive and less compulsive ways to do this.
In Oregon, designers are experimenting with providing drivers with different options.
They can choose a device with or without GPS.
Or they might abandon the device altogether, deciding instead to pay a fixed fee based on the average number of miles that all residents of the state travel.
In other places, they hope to sell the idea to an alert public, forcing devices to do more, not less.
In New York, transport officials are seeking to develop a tax device that will also accept payments on parking counters, provide “pay as you drive” insurance, and collect a real-time pool of speed data from other drivers that drivers could use to avoid traffic jams.
“Automobilists will be attracted to participate in the benefits they will be offered,” the city planning document says.
Some transportation system designers, however, are wondering whether all the talk about mispayment is just a huge distraction.
In the San Francisco Bay Area City Transportation Commission, officials say Congress could very easily overcome the bankruptcy of the Highway Construction Trust Fund by raising gasoline taxes.
An additional one-time or annual tax could be levied on hybrid car drivers and other persons whose vehicles do not use a lot of gasoline so that they pay their fair share.
“There is no need for radical surgery when all you need to do is take aspirin,” said Randy Rantzler, director of the Commission on Legislation and Public Relations.
If we do this, hundreds of millions of drivers will worry about their privacy and a lot of other things.
EU prepares measures to support Ukraine in case of economic pressure from Russia
The European Union has a reserve plan to provide Ukraine with gas, as well as to reach an agreement with the IMF on an emergency loan, if Russia takes any measures in response to the possible signing of the EU-Ukraine association treaty at the Vilnius summit.
Negotiations are ongoing with the IMF on a stand-by loan, and another EU official directly involved in the negotiations added that their aim is to conclude an agreement soon.
In addition to a potential loan from the IMF, Ukraine could receive 610 million euros from the European Union itself.
Analysts interviewed by Reuters doubt that Ukraine and the IMF are able to overcome long-standing disagreements about financing conditions.
Not believe in the possibility of reforms necessary to receive aid, and the international rating agency S&P, which lowered on Friday the sovereign rating of Ukraine by one stage - to "B-" from "B".
However, EU representatives say that the IMF may be flexible in terms of lending, taking into account the circumstances of Ukraine.
