Russia out of the fight for the pollution of cities by cars
Attempts to solve the transport problems of major cities have been observed in most of the world’s metropolis since the second half of the twentieth century.
As a rule, it was either about their rearrangement and expansion of highways, or about attempts to reduce the demand for car trips, the number of cars and the time of their use.
A well-known example is Singapore, where a strict quota is introduced for the increase in the number of private cars, and the right to purchase them is purchased at auctions.
Its price can be two to three times the price of the car itself.
European cities, including London, have introduced a fee for entering the city center.
In Germany, such as Hamburg and Stuttgart, so-called green zones are introduced, where only cars with a certain eco class that also use high-quality fuels (including biofuels or electric vehicles) are allowed to enter.
Beijing’s Environmental Protection Agency, for example, approved in 2012 a “five-year clean air plan” worth about 250 billion yuan ($40 billion).
Li Kunsheng, director of the Department of Transport Pollution Control of the Municipal Environmental Protection Bureau of Beijing, said that the main goal of the five-year plan is to reduce the leading air pollutants by 20-35% by 2017, increase the number of private cars to the level not exceeding 6 million (now 5.2 million), and increase the use of fuel by not more than 5% per vehicle.
According to the agency, currently motor transport in Beijing is responsible for 22.5% of total air pollution.
Among the main measures of the program is the restriction of the use of road transport, as well as the introduction of additional taxes for car owners.
Among other measures, the “green five-year” measures include the accelerated transition to euro-fuel standards compared to the rest of the country, the introduction of a local system of eco-standards and marking of cars and fuels, the restriction on car entrance to the central part of the city, the ban on the use of outdated vehicles (in addition, the creation of incentive financial programs to replace old cars with hybrid or electric vehicles), the development of electric transport (including public and official), the development of public transport (including high-speed).
Among Beijing’s automotive innovations is also the prohibition for all private cars to move within the fifth transport ring (a total of six in the capital of the People’s Republic of China) one day a week (the corresponding information is contained in the vehicle number mark), as well as the issuance of registration signs for cars on the basis of a lottery (for example, in 2011, the first year of the lottery, the total number of registration permits for private cars in Beijing amounted to only a third of the number of 2010).
According to the current state program "Environmental protection for 2012-2020", the number of cities with high and very high air pollution should be reduced to 128 (in 2012 they were 138).
According to the Ministry of Nature, in 2011 "moving sources" accounted for 41% of all emissions of pollutants into the atmosphere of cities.
In Moscow, for example, emissions from cars are ten times higher than industrial emissions, and in St. Petersburg - nine times.
Russia is only beginning to think about the possibilities of restrictive regulation of cars on the streets of cities.
The director of the Institute of Transport Economy and Transport Policy of VŠE Mikhail Blinkin believes that administrative and fiscal measures aimed at suppressing the demand for motor travel are obviously unpopular, they can be adopted by society only under the condition of their fullest universality.
In the case of Moscow there is a unique problem related to the structure of its fleet, where there are two clusters weakly sensitive to any regulatory influences - official and personal cars, as well as cars of "privileged" users, the total number of which is at least 200 thousand (about 5% of the total number of the fleet of Moscow).
Recently, urbanists from the ECOM center in St. Petersburg prepared a study where the balance of urban territories between residential buildings, the area of road coverage and the number of motor vehicles is analyzed.
The main findings of the researchers: the city center is equipped with roads twice as little as required, and most motorists living in the center do not use cars every day, leaving them for long periods of time on parking lots or just on the streets.
As a result, it is proposed to build not parking, but storage of cars, not to expand, but to reduce the road (so that the streets become more friendly to pedestrians), as well as to limit the use and placement of personal transport within the limits of the territory of the protected zone of the historic center (a common territory of about 3212 hectares, covering a number of central districts of the city).
