Goldman Sachs warns of risks to the Russian economy
Goldman Sachs has warned of rising risks for the main driver of fragile economic growth in Russia – consumption.
This is primarily a crisis of non-payment on unsecured consumer loans and massive reductions of workers.
Our main concern now is not that growth has slowed down, but rather the structure of that growth.
Recently, it is entirely due to consumption, which almost does not reduce turnover,” said Goldman Sachs chief economist for Russia Clemens Grafe, presenting yesterday the quarterly report of the investment bank on the Russian economy.
The nominal wage growth in Russia is now around 10%.
With inflation of 6%, it will be able to provide future consumer demand at approximately the current level, Goldman Sachs expects.
But the profitability of Russian companies is falling, so, most likely, they will be dealing with the optimization of personnel expenses.
Today we see a significant increase in the share of wages in GDP: if wages grow by 10%, then GDP - only by 2%, - explained Mr. Grafe.
Companies have experienced a decrease in profitability.
If it does not grow, it can lead to redundancies and increased unemployment.
The Russian business cannot not raise wages, commented Barclays Capital’s chief economist for Russia and the CIS Vladimir Pantyushin.
Unemployment is close to historic lows and the competition for workers is high.
In order to remove or retain existing employees, employers have to raise wages.
Consumption in Russia is supported by a very rapid growth in credit demand.
According to Mr. Grafe, due to the extremely high rates on consumer loans, this type of lending does not have a multiplicative effect on the country’s economy.
"We have not seen any benefits for the economy from the growth of credit, the money does not differ in the economy, but returns to the same banks in the form of interest payments," the economist said.
But the problem is another – Goldman Sachs expects a rise in default on unsecured loans.
They are mostly taken by poor people who have nothing to provide.
Interest rates on such loans are high.
As a result, they are not returned more often,” said Mr. Grafe.
Therefore, the second threat to the growth of the Russian economy is a possible crisis of non-payments on unsecured loans.
The director of the Banking Institute of VŠE Vasily Solodkov already sees the signs of a rising banking crisis.
Small credit institutions, having no access to the cheap resources available to state banks, were forced to attract public funds at high interest rates.
In response, state banks went on the path of war and began to reduce credit rates, continues the economist.
Small credit institutions cannot issue loans at the same interest rates, otherwise they will have a negative interest margin.
If the state banks do not give up the dumping, Russia threatens a full-fledged banking crisis, believes Vasily Solodkov.
The deprivation of licenses of a number of banks in recent weeks the economist considers the forerunner of a massive collapse.
"State banks themselves will not cope with such a situation: the deposit insurance system was not initially designed for a systemic crisis," the head of the institute warns.
But the growth of consumption will slow down without a crisis of non-payments, the investment bank believes, because of the refusal to index the salaries of civil servants and the military, laid down in the current version of the budget.
In part, the impact on consumption will be mitigated by freezing the tariffs of natural monopolies (and, as a consequence, a decrease in inflation).
But only partially: if investments do not grow (and there are no prerequisites for this yet - see the certificate), the growth of consumption will still slow, Goldman Sachs is confident.
Vladimir Pantyushin of Barclays Capital does not yet see the prerequisites for the implementation of pessimistic scenarios.
“The main risk is still the fall in the price of oil,” he says.
According to his estimate, the Russian economy will begin to shrink when the price of oil is below $90 / barrel.
Goldman Sachs also noted that the central bank is not yet able to lower interest rates in the economy.
There is a paradoxical picture: inflation has decreased, and banks have started to raise rates.
This may mean that they didn’t believe the central bank that announced the transition to inflation targeting,” said Clemens Grafe.
The central bank’s interest policy does not affect market rates, it only affects interbank lending rates.
"For the Central Bank, this is the collapse of all hopes," said Clemens Grafe.
The money received at the auctions of the Central Bank is not used by banks to lend the economy, but to manage its liquidity.
As soon as the rate drops, the exchange rate immediately changes, which means that the funds are trying to go on speculation against the ruble.
“Earlier or later, the Central Bank will realize that this strategy does not work,” Grafe said and reminded that the state plans to allow the ruble to “free float” by the end of 2015.
But it will either have to do it sooner or raise the key interest rate of the central bank (5,5%), he believes.
According to him, the rate of the ruble is now artificially overpriced by 10%.
I have only one way – to lose weight, concludes the expert.
But if the central bank plunges in the financiers even a shadow of doubt that the liquidation of the currency corridor is not part of the policy to weaken the ruble, it can crash the ruble much stronger.
