Snowden is ready to "cooperate" with Germany on the issue of US intelligence
Edward Snowden, a U.S. intelligence agent, said he was ready to go to Berlin to testify to the German parliament if the U.S. National Security Agency and its director Keith Alexander were unable to answer questions about their activities.
German MP Hans-Christian Straubele met with Snowden in Russia on Thursday, where he was granted asylum, to discuss his testimony in Germany.
A letter from Mr. Snowden, which the MP presented to the media in Berlin on Friday, said: “Al the outcome of my efforts has been clearly positive, my government continues to treat dissent as betrayal and seeks to criminalize political statements with criminal charges that provide no protection.”
Speaking the truth is not a crime.
In the letter, Snowden said he believes the support of the international community could convince the U.S. government to abandon criminal charges against him.
The charges filed by the U.S. Department of Justice include espionage and theft of state property.
German Interior Minister Hans-Peter Friedrich told Zeit Online: “If Mr. Snowden is willing to talk to German officials, we will find ways to make it possible.”
Relations between the United States and Germany became tense after allegations that the NSA had intercepted the phone of Chancellor Angela Merkel.
Thomas Opperman, a MP who heads the parliamentary group overseeing the intelligence service, said that if there is an opportunity to hear Mr. Snowden as a witness “without putting him at risk or destroying relations with the United States altogether,” it should be used.
Mr. Strebele, a member of parliament from the German Green Party, posted his photo with Mr. Snowden on his Twitter.
During his visit to Russia he was accompanied by two German journalists.
Mr. Strebele said that, according to the lawyer of the former NSA contractor, Mr. Snowden could not have returned to Russia if he had left.
If Mr. Snowden were to testify in Germany, he would need guarantees that he would be there “safe,” the MP said.
Snowden said in his letter that he faced a “hard and persistent” campaign of persecution that forced him to leave his home.
However, he said he was inspired by the world’s reaction to “his political statements.”
Citizens around the world, as well as senior officials — including in the United States — have seen the exposure of the uncontrolled system of pervasive surveillance as beneficial to society.
The letter contains a proposal to cooperate with the German authorities “when the difficulties of this humanitarian situation are solved.”
Frontier Airlines will charge for hand luggage
Frontier Airlines plans to charge passengers up to $100 for carrying hand luggage on board their flight.
Frontier Airlines plans to start charging up to $100 for hand luggage and $2 for coffee or soda, although their announcement on Wednesday said passengers would be able to keep their entire bag.
The new baggage fee extends to bags in the upper luggage compartment, so small bags placed underneath the seat will remain free.
Frontier said it would charge $25 if the fee is paid in advance, and $100 if travellers would only pay when they were on board.
Frontier spokeswoman Kate O'Malley said the $100 fee should make passengers pay in advance.
“We don’t want to charge for that,” she said.
Airlines started charging the first and second baggage in 2008.
Passengers trying to avoid these charges put as much as they can in hand luggage placed in the upper luggage compartments, which often leaves no space in these compartments.
Fee is one way to make passengers carry less on board.
O’Malley said the new collection wasn’t really for making money.
The fact is that the most loyal customers of Frontier say that finding a place in the upper luggage compartment is becoming more and more difficult.
Passengers who buy tickets on the airline’s website will not have to pay.
This means that one passenger in a row at the departure of the Frontier flight can get the opportunity to carry a bag for free, while the next passenger in a row can pay $100 for the same bag.
O’Malley said the change in procedures on the website and at the Frontier checkpoints is meant to ensure that passengers are aware of the fee before they get on board.
The new Frontier charge for hand luggage will not start to be charged before the summer, although a date has not yet been set.
Passengers often complain about luggage fees and other charges, but airlines love them.
They argue that baggage handling costs money, and passengers who need this service have to pay for it.
Many on Wall Street consider the addition of luggage charges a sign that airlines are charging enough money to cover the cost of flights after several years of losses.
However, most of them were not related to hand luggage charges.
Spirit Airlines Inc. introduced the first hand luggage fee three years ago, and another Allegiant Air discount later followed its example.
The only other airline with such a fee is Hungarian Wizz Air, airline consultant Jay Sorensen said, who is closely monitoring the additional fees.
According to his estimate in a December 2011 report, the collection for hand luggage brings Spirit $50 million a year.
Sorenzen, a former top manager at Midwest Airlines, recently flew a Spirit flight, and was curious about what he would find at the take-off when passengers encountered an unusual Spirit collection for hand luggage.
“The landing process was the smoothest I’ve seen in my career in airlines,” he said.
I expected to see teeth scratching and fighting at the landing.
The plane was full, he said, “and the landing went fast.”
Frontier also follows Spirit for a $2 fee for coffee, tea, soda or juice.
Frontier said that passengers who receive a soda or juice can keep the entire bowl and that a portion of coffee will be provided for free.
They will still provide free water.
US Airways attempted to charge for drinks for a short time in 2008, but refused to do so seven months later after passengers started complaining and no other major airline followed her example.
The Frontier initiative to charge for hand luggage when passengers do not buy tickets directly from the airline is its latest measure to attract customers to its website.
Airlines pay online ticket dealers, such as Orbitz, between $10 and $25 for each ticket sold.
This has given all airlines an incentive to encourage passengers to buy tickets directly from them rather than contact an online travel agency.
However, Frontier went beyond everyone in this area.
In September, it began giving twice as much of the bonus miles of frequent flying passengers to customers who bought tickets through an online travel agency.
On Wednesday, she cut the premium number of miles to 25 percent of the miles of travel.
For example, a 1,000 mile journey from Frontier, purchased from an online travel agency, would allow you to get 250 miles.
In addition, passengers can choose a seat in advance only if they buy tickets directly on the Frontier website.
Frontier has a base of loyal customers in its hometown of Denver, but its business is shrinking and becoming profitable.
Revenue declined by 9 percent, and flight capabilities fell by 13 percent in the first quarter, according to financial results released on Wednesday by parent company Republic Airways Holdings Inc.
Republic is trying to fix the finances of Frontier as part of the sale of the airline.
NSA blames "internal error" and not hackers in stopping the site
The National Security Agency said on Friday evening that the shutdown of their site for several hours caused a technical failure, not hackers, as claimed on the network.
“NSA.gov was unavailable for several hours tonight due to an internal error that occurred during the scheduled update,” the intelligence agency said in an official email.
The problem will be resolved tonight.
The claims that the disruption was caused by a distributed DDoS attack are false.
Earlier this evening, online server monitoring systems recorded that the NSA website had not been working for at least six hours and the site was still inaccessible to some users.
Earlier, a NSA spokesman told ABC News that the agency’s internal secret network was “not at all” hacked.
No classified information is at risk, the representative said.
At least one online group of activist hackers said it was responsible for disrupting the NSA website through a DDoS attack.
DDoS attacks are designed to overwhelm the target site with traffic until the servers are overloaded and the site fails.
The hacking tactics are relatively simple, and the attacks are not intended to penetrate the internal network of the target system.
The previously super-secret NSA, once nicknamed “No Such Agency,” has been at the center of public attention and fierce criticism in recent months after a series of disclosures about its extensive overseas and domestic surveillance programs — all in response to NSA secret files stolen from the agency and published by disappointed former NSA employee Edward Snowden.
Growing controversy around the agency has sparked speculation that today’s incident was the result of targeted actions by hackers.
Bombardier profits decline with drop in aircraft orders and supplies
Bombardier Corporation, a Canadian aircraft and train manufacturer, on Thursday a 15% decrease in net profit due to declining aircraft orders and deliveries in the third quarter and contractual issues in its railway division.
Bombardier, based in Montreal, has also not released any data on flight tests of its latest CSeries aircraft and has not provided any new information on whether ambitious plans to put the aircraft into commercial operation by next September will be fulfilled.
After the first flight of the pilot aircraft, which took place about a month and a half ago, it flew only three times, which raises questions about whether the test stage is on schedule.
The results failed to meet the forecasts and led to a fall of more than 8 percent on the Toronto Stock Exchange.
Cameron Dorxen, an analyst at National Bank Financial, lowered his assessment from “above the market average” to “average market” on Thursday because of the belief that stock growth is limited to the next quarter or two.
“While the decline in aircraft deliveries was generally predictable, we are disappointed with the transport sector’s earnings,” Dorxen said in a stock market review.
We believe Bombardier will receive new orders for CSeries as its flight testing program continues.
However, if no new orders are announced in the coming months, we assume that the market will become more skeptical of the program.
Bombardier hopes that the CSeries family of aircraft will allow it to win a place in the lower price segment, where Boeing and Airbus currently dominate.
The first pilot aircraft was introduced in March and made its first flight in September after several months of delay.
However, there are not too many firm orders for the CSeries yet – 177, as potential buyers are waiting for the results of flight tests to check the company’s claims on fuel efficiency and potential economy of the new aircraft.
There are currently 403 orders and arrangements with 15 customers and operators.
Chief Executive Officer Pierre Bodouan was confident that Bombardier would reach its target of 300 solid orders by the time the first aircraft is put into commercial operation.
On Thursday, executives also assured analysts and the media that the program is moving forward as planned.
"The test model of the aircraft did not stay on the ground longer than expected," Boduan said during a phone conference, adding that ground tests and software updates were scheduled for the time of the aircraft's standstill.
All manufacturers plan tests differently.
We decided to take the first flight and take a break for updates, so we did.
This will be the case throughout the flight tests.
The second of the five test samples is expected to fly in the coming weeks and all the others will soon follow him, the company said.
And yet analysts are skeptical of the statement that the first customer will be able to start operations of the CSeries aircraft 12 months after its first flight.
Bombardier said it is evaluating the timing of the commissioning and will provide new information in the coming months.
“This slow pace of flight testing – although apparently in line with Bombardier’s internal schedule – supports our view that the launch will be postponed to the first quarter of 2015,” said Doerxen.
In the third quarter ended September 30, Bombardier’s net revenue fell to $147 million, or 8 cents per share, from $172 million, or 9 cents per share, last year.
The adjusted profit per share remained the same – 9 cents.
Gross income decreased slightly – from $4.2 to $4.1 billion.
Analysts expected a profit of 10 cents per share and gross revenue of $4.56 billion, according to Thomson Reuters I/B/E/S.
The world’s fourth largest aircraft manufacturer said it had delivered 45 aircraft per quarter, down from the previous year’s 57.
The total number of orders fell from 83 to 26.
The portfolio of orders of the aerospace department amounted to $32.9 billion as of September 30, unchanged since December 31.
"In the aerospace field, the results were in line with our goals, but the small number of incoming orders and general market conditions have become an unpleasant factor," said Boduan.
Gross revenue in the aerospace direction fell by 13 percent to $ 2 billion.
Bombardier, the world’s largest train manufacturer, said gross revenue in the sector grew by 11 percent to $2.1 billion.
The portfolio of orders in the transport division amounted to $32.6 billion as of September 30, which is slightly higher than the 31st of December.
The revenue of the transport unit was negatively affected by problems with the execution of several major contracts.
The management said that a new development plan will be presented in the fourth quarter.
Bombardier’s shares, which also announced that Google’s chief financial officer Patrick Pichett will join the board of directors, fell by 8.5 percent to $4.83 on Thursday’s trading.
Brazil’s Embraer SA, the world’s third largest commercial aircraft manufacturer and Bombardier’s closest competitor, a quarterly revenue decrease of 10 percent on Thursday.
Sony expects lower annual earnings
The Japanese electronics manufacturer, Sony Corporation, concluded the previous quarter with a net loss of 19.3 billion yen, or $197 million, reduced its forecast of profit for the current fiscal year.
Sony’s results from July to September 2013 were worse than expected due to falling demand for TVs, video cameras and personal computers produced by the Japanese corporation.
Sony's television business, which in the second quarter brought the company the first in three years operating profit of 5.2 billion yen, in the reporting period again fell to 9.3 billion yen operating loss.
The Japanese consumer electronics market is experiencing tough times, especially due to the decline in demand for TVs.
And while competitors are looking for a way out of the difficult situation, Sony continues to focus on the consumer segment.
