The speech gene stimulates the formation of synapses.
Scientists from John Hopkins University and Mount Sinai School of Medicine have discovered a protein thanks to which the "speech gene" Foxp2 performs its function by stimulating the formation of new connections between neurons.
The study is published in Science, on the website of the journal you can read its brief content.
The Foxp2 gene is the first known gene whose function is directly related to speech.
His role was established in 2001 by the discovery of a family of several people who could not correctly pronounce words and sometimes did not even understand each other.
The scientists found that members of the family had disrupted the work of the Foxp2 gene, but how it performs its function remains unknown.
In a new study, biologists showed that at least part of Foxp2’s function is to stimulate the formation of new synapses in the area of the brain associated with speech formation.
He does this thanks to another gene, SRPX2.
The latter was discovered as a result of the search for factors that stimulate the formation of synapses.
SRPX2 was one of 10 similar genes found by the authors, with only its activity being influenced by Foxp2.
That SRPX2 really affects vocalization, scientists confirmed in a mouse experiment.
When the genetic activity was artificially reduced in animals, they cried less when separated from their mother.
If the activity of the gene was restored, the frequency of the sounds issued was also restored.
Previously, the mice also showed a connection with the vocalization of Foxp2 itself.
Animals who were given a human copy of the gene ate more actively and at a lower frequency than ordinary mice.
To date, however, scientists do not know whether the work of Foxp2 and, consequently, the SRPX2 it operates is associated with purely "mechanical" properties of sound formation or more subtle processes.
