Shortly after the transfer, Scarborough repeatedly called Ditt, who was at dinner at the Iwood Park football stadium of the Blackburn Rovers team.
The lawyer returned home for drugs; there were nine conversations between them.
The court learned that Ditta “regularly consumed” cocaine after tests found traces of class A drug in his hair, wallet and credit cards.
Ditta was later arrested, but denied cocaine use, said he had spoken to the suspected dealer because he was his client, and insisted that their communication constituted a "lawyer's secret".
During his detention, Ditta took his wallet and tried to withdraw several credit cards, but all of them were confiscated, and a hair sample was also taken from him.
During the police interrogation, he said that besides his workplace, he had a home office, and clients were coming home to him for legal matters.
However, the court became aware that after important arrests he called the biggest drug traffickers, a number of whom he had previously represented in court, to tell that detectives knew about them.
