Ditta refused to admit guilt and said: "If I were a corrupt lawyer, which I am not, and wanted to pass on information to Mr. Scarborough, I would not have waited 15 hours, I would have done it immediately."
But after the meeting, senior officer Lee Holsted of the Lancashire Police said: “Mr. Ditta turned from a criminal attorney to a criminal criminal as soon as he began buying drugs from organized crime.”
His addiction to cocaine has made him hopelessly compromised and vulnerable to the targets of the main members of criminal groups who commissioned him to extract valuable information about police investigations.
Lawyers must follow the highest standards of professional ethics and inspire public trust and confidence.
Mr. Ditta betrayed that trust and tried to cover up his profession.
The investigation of Mr. Ditt was conducted by Lancashire’s Special Dangerous Organized Crime Unit, which has already been convicted of three cases of cocaine possession and now of obstruction of justice, demonstrating our commitment to achieving fair punishment for criminals.
