The court suspended the execution of the decision on the practice of "stop-and-search" in the New York Police Department
On Thursday, the Federal District Court of Appeal suspended the enforcement of a court order demanding changes to the New York Police Department's "stop-and-search" program and removed the judge from the case.
The U.S. Second District Court of Appeal has said that the enforcement of judge Shira Sheindlin's decisions will be suspended until the results of the appeal filed by the city are received.
In August, the judge ruled that the city violated the constitution in the way it carried out a program of street arrests and interrogations.
The city filed an appeal against its decision and resolutions on corrective measures, including an order to appoint a controller to help the police department change its work practices and associated training program.
On Thursday, the Court of Appeal heard the debates of the parties on the petition for the suspension of the case.
The Court of Appeal said it was necessary to remove the judge because she violated the code of conduct of U.S. judges and did not consider it necessary to avoid demonstrating bias, in part due to a series of media interviews and official statements containing a public response to the court’s criticism.
The judge ruled that police officers violated the civil rights of tens of thousands of people by unreasonably appealing to blacks and Latin Americans under the “stop and search” program.
It has appointed an external controller to oversee large-scale changes that include policy, training and control reforms, and has decided to launch a pilot program to test body-fixed video cameras in the police stations where most arrests take place.
In August, New York City decided to stop the practice of storing the names and addresses of people whose affairs were terminated after a police check.
The hearing on the city’s appeal should take place after March 14, 2014.
The “stop and search” tactic has been criticized by many civil rights lawyers.
"Stop-search" has been practiced for decades in one form or another, but the number of documented stops has increased dramatically under the administration of independent mayor Michael Bloomberg, reaching an absolute record in 2011 of 684,330 people, most of whom are black and Latin Americans.
In 2004, four people, all representatives of national minorities, filed a collective lawsuit with the court.
Supporters of changes to the Stop-and-Seek program at the New York Police Department say these changes will put an end to unfair practices, form a more reliable and efficient police service, and may affect how other police departments implement this practice.
Opponents argue that the changes will lower the fighting spirit of policemen rather than the level of crime, lead to unnecessary spending of money and will not solve the more global problem of complex conditions in the police because of the decrease in the number of officers by several thousand over the past decade.
The judge noted that it does not stop the "stop-and-search" practice, which is in line with the constitution, but changes the way New York police stop people.
