Parents of intersex children can choose “uncertain gender”
Germany became the first European country to recognize a third gender in children born with external genitals of the intermediate type.
Newborns will no longer have to be attributed to male or female sex.
The new law does not require parents to name any gender of such children, allowing parents to indicate gender as “uncertain” or “unidentified” in their birth certificates.
The aim of the law was to relieve pressure from parents who can make hasty decisions about surgery to assign gender to newborns, and to counter discrimination against intersex people.
One intersex man, according to the BBC, said many years later, “I’m neither a man nor a woman.”
I will remain a scratch product created by doctors with scratches and scars.
Approximately one in two thousand babies born annually is neither a boy nor a girl.
They have intersexuality, one of approximately 60 pathological conditions that fall under the diagnosis of “sexual disorder” – a collective term for people with atypical chromosomes, gonads (ovaries or testicles) or abnormally developed external genitals.
Wallis Simpson may have been intersex.
Gender identification has not yet been sufficiently studied, but most experts in the U.S. say that if the gender cannot be determined, it is better to use all available information and assign it than to wait and monitor the psychological and physical development of the child before the operation, if at all this happens.
New York psychiatrist Dr. Jack Drecher, who specializes in gender identity issues, said the new German law “sounds like a good idea.”
Intersex children create an ethical dilemma.
“Some people have life-threatening disorders that require surgery, but most children don’t,” he said.
You can assign gender without surgery and then see how the personality develops.
The science of how a child will develop any gender identity is not very accurate.
No one can answer the question of why this happens.
It’s like a mystery about why people are homosexual.
A report sent to the European Commission in 2011 describes intersex people as different from transgender or transgender people because their condition is not related to gender, but to their biological structure, which does not correspond exclusively to either male or female gender, but is typical for both at the same time or is not characteristic of either.
These characteristics can be manifested in secondary sexual characteristics such as muscle mass, hair distribution, chest and bodybuilding; primary sexual characteristics such as reproductive organs and genitals, or in the structure of chromosomes and hormones.
The report also provides an overview of the discrimination that intersex and transgender people face in employment, as well as the level of oppression, cruelty and prejudice-based crime.
Boys with gender disorders now have a special camp.
Australia and Nepal are already allowing adults to include male, female or “third gender” in their official documents.
In June, 52-year-old Australian resident Norri May-Welby became the world’s first person to be recognized as “sexless”, defending in court the right to retain “uncertain” sexual status for life.
