At any time, birds could die from electrical discharge.
And the locals were at risk of leaving without light due to the damage of wires.
Therefore, linear monitors started the operation to rescue the nest, and not for the first time in our practice.
Scientists-ornitologists from the Dnipropetrovsk National University helped to develop a scheme for transferring the nest.
They also conducted training for staff of the regional networks.
The renowned Dnipropetrovsk ornithologist Alexander Ponomarenko advised energy professionals on all stages of the reconstruction of the nests.
It is estimated that there are more than 50 "apartments" in the area in emergency condition.
For their reconstruction, special metal platforms were welded, resembling a vortex.
The base was splintered with barbed branches, and then the old nest was moved there.
According to experts, it is enough to lay the old branches as a foundation so that the birds recognize the nest and return to it.
Later, they will build their own houses.
A month ago, the first nest was reconstructed in the village of Peschanka in the Novomoskovsk region.
Near the electrical support was placed a new iron concrete pillar and placed on it a platform with an old, already worn nest.
The entire operation cost the energy companies nine thousand hryvnia.
And the other day, the same new residence took place in the village of Ivanovka of the Petroivsky district in the basement of grandmother Anya.
Here the platform was fixed in the previous place, only raised over wires.
Ornithologists are confident that cautious, conservative birds will not even notice in the spring that their "apartment" has undergone major repairs.
By the end of the year, the same reconstruction awaits four other nests in the Pokrovsk and Tsarishan districts of Dnipropetrovsk.
By the way, while some rescue rare birds, others mercilessly kill them.
