George Kerevan: Breakdown with Europe gives Scots a choice
Another day, another fear of independence.
This time we are warned that an independent Scotland will have to join the pan-European Free Movement Area as a condition for membership in the EU.
There is a series of stories about passport control in Berwick and the border with a clutch wire along Adriano's shaft.
True, the Strathclyde newspaper pointed out the possible economic benefits of more free movement across the rest of Europe, although — predictably — this did not appear in the headlines.
No one has pointed out that EU member states are spending a lot of time reversing their formal rules as they find it convenient.
Since Scotland is not currently part of the Schengen area, the continued non-compliance would be a cheap concession for Brussels in return for what it really wanted from the Scots.
This is not a story worthy of attention.
And so old that it turned into a fossil: for the first time I heard the “utka” about “independence means passport control” at least 40 years ago.
And yet there is an interesting moment lost in the re-telling of an old tale.
Why should an independent Scotland obey the orders of Europe?
Why change the yacht of London to the yacht of Brussels, especially now?
Here is the real European news: the great post-war plan to unite Europe has finally stalled.
With the euro crisis, the project “Europe” is officially dead.
Thro the European Union, parties that oppose the EU or advocate the abolition of the euro as a single currency are gaining strength.
Even in Germany, the eurosceptic Alternative for Germany party – founded this year only – emerged from nowhere and won almost five million votes in the September federal elections, thus essentially pushing the “Free Democrats” (an analogue to our “Liberal Democrats”) out of the Bundestag.
There has always been an internal opposition to the plan of creating a federal Europe.
Nevertheless, the current economic crisis has become a turning point.
The austerity measures imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank, and the chains imposed on national economies through the preservation of a single currency, have led many to think that the “Europe” project has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with the fact that national governments are working with excessive budget deficits, which was only true for Greece.
In fact, the Eurosystem has blocked its members at exchange rates favorable to German exporters, which German politicians want to keep.
Without the possibility of devaluing the national currency, Southern Europe is in a previously disadvantaged position in terms of production capacity compared to Germany.
The only rescue is to cut salaries and government spending, which is actively supported by Berlin.
Behind the current budget and currency challenges lies a deeper problem of Europe’s productive capabilities.
As a result of the package of green energy measures implemented by Brussels — a code that means subsidizing French and German energy companies at the expense of consumers — the European industry pays twice as much for electricity and four times as much for gas than in the United States.
These are paralytically unfavourable price conditions, as we have seen in Grindelwald.
No freezing of wages in the world will stop the devastating victory of cheap U.S. shale gas over the European petrochemical industry.
The result is a riot, especially in France, once the most fervent supporter of the EU.
After the war, the French political elite saw the EU as a way to control Germany and put Paris at the same level as Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a means of gaining political legitimacy, and has already imposed its own economic policy on Europe, leaving the ruined French economy in a disaster.
The result is that Marine Le Pen’s right-wing, anti-EU party National Front has just won decisive additional elections, bringing the ruling Socialist Party to third place.
The Front is now the most popular party in France with 24 percent of the votes – a timely warning to British Labour that one cannot assume that a right-wing split will automatically benefit the left.
What does Le Pen do with her newly gained popularity among the French white working class?
She wants to use the EU elections next year to create a bloc in the European Parliament against the EU and against the single currency.
If — and this is very likely — anti-EU parties get support at these elections, such a bloc will be able to take a dominant position in the European Parliament for the first time.
This is my opinion: soon the growing anti-EU and anti-unified currency sentiment in Europe will merge together to destroy the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but it will again become something like a vague “Europe of (sovereign) nations” that liked General de Gaulle.
Germany and several dependent economies could keep the euro, but France and Southern Europe will restore their own currencies.
I assume that Britain is distancing itself from this project, hoping to get closer to the United States.
Nevertheless, Washington’s growing interest in the Pacific indicates the likelihood that Britain will be ignored in the cold of the Atlantic.
In what situation does this leave Scotland?
We can choose to become a region of Little England.
Or we can defend our own economic interests, which means, among other things, sending Berlin and Brussels to the hell.
I suspect that Scotland will succeed in a more free European arrangement if we keep our currency.
Cooperation with other like-minded countries will be easier in a non-federal Europe of nations.
Otherwise, we should consider repeating the experience of Norway and preserving our economic independence.
The Scottish National Party government in Scotland is – strangely enough – the most successful political movement in Europe against austerity measures, which received an impressive majority of votes in 2011 thanks to objections to spending cuts proposed (and implemented) by Labour Treasury Chancellor Alister Darling and the subsequent Tory and Liberal Democrats coalition.
It would be ridiculous for Scotland now to vote for independence only to take the austerity measures imposed by Berlin and Brussels.
Early Puberty: Early Ageing
African and Latin American girls tend to reach sexual maturity earlier than their white peers, research shows.
Physical changes do not mean that puberty is close.
There is no evidence that hormones or other chemicals are to blame.
Experts believe that the obesity epidemic may be one of the trigger mechanisms of early puberty
The tendency to early sexual maturity is not so pronounced in boys
Former CNN correspondent Pat Eteridge is a journalist specializing in child health and family affairs.
Should a mother be frightened if her daughter starts to form mammary seeds and grows pubic hair at 7 or 8 years of age?
At the annual conference of the American Academy of Pediatrics this week in Orlando, Florida, pediatric endocrinologist Dr. Paul Kaplovitz explained that these early physical changes are quite common among American girls and represent a new norm.
“I spend a lot of time reassuring my parents—usually this doesn’t mean a quick start to full sexual maturity,” Kaplovitz said.
Obvious signs of development, such as growing breasts, pubic and hip hair and body odor, appear earlier in girls.
But there has been only a small shift in the age of menarche (first menstruation) over the last four decades.
In the United States, the average age is 12.5 years and has dropped from 12.75 in 1970.
“After the breast begins to develop, it takes at least two to three years before the menarche,” said Kaplovitz, who is also the author of the book “Early puberty in girls: How to cope with this common problem.”
Time is the most accurate test of how puberty will progress.
There is a discussion about what represents the actual onset of sexual maturity, but is considered “preterm” when breast enlargement is accompanied by a sharp increase in growth up to 8 years.
In most cases, the process will slow down or stop — this is something that the pediatrician can monitor closely.
A faster progression can serve as a basis for tests with an endocrinologist to rule out serious problems such as tumors or cysts.
There are procedures to delay early menstruation and prevent another consequence: premature bone aging, which can ultimately lead to slowed growth and low growth in adulthood.
Recommendations for drug or hormone therapy are based on the child’s age, level of development, growth rate and emotional maturity.
Psychosocial aspects are also important.
Kaplovitz is cautious with drugs, but admits that “suppression of puberty can mitigate behavioral problems and girls’ feelings that they are different from their peers.”
Another big problem is clear: parents just don’t want their very young daughters to have menstruation.
“They’re worried about the risk of pregnancy or even how they’ll deal with hygiene issues,” Kaplovitz said.
“It was a shock,” recalls one woman whose daughter had menstruation at the age of 10.
Although there were signs and we talked about menstruation, she wasn’t emotionally ready.
She came home from school frightened and upset that she was the first among her friends.
There are many theories about the causes of early puberty.
However, there is no consistent evidence that hormones in milk or other foods, chemicals in the environment, or sexual messages in the media are to blame.
In boys, like in girls, puberty occurs earlier.
Kaplovitz argues that the premise that has the greatest weight is the obesity epidemic.
In 2001, he helped conduct a study of girls aged 6 to 9, which linked the amount of body fat with the periods of puberty.
Other evidence supports this conclusion, but there are many other contributing factors.
In this country, African and Latin American girls tend to reach sexual maturity earlier than their white peers.
There are various explanations.
Around the world, early puberty seems to be influenced by everything, from economic conditions and climate to genes.
Another mystery: although boys have hair on the face and scalp appear at a younger age, the tendency to complete early puberty is not as pronounced as in girls.
Other doctors attending the AAP conference confirmed the complexity of this topic.
The appearance of acne and pubic hair occurs even in infants and children of the young age.
“We need to be careful about how we determine the true onset of sexual maturity,” said Dr. Lawrence Silverman, a pediatric endocrinologist at Goryeeb Children’s Hospital in Morristawn, New Jersey.
Parents should not be embarrassed to receive instructions from a pediatrician on how to talk to their child.
“This could mean a earlier conversation than expected,” Kaplovitz explained.
If you remain calm, your child will usually react well.
Girls who bloom early need confirmation that even when it happens earlier, this process is a normal part of life.
