New anti-nicotine vaccine could deprive smoking of pleasure
Scientists have developed an anti-nicotine vaccine that could deprive the process of smoking cigarettes of pleasure.
One dose of the vaccine was able to protect mice from nicotine addiction for a lifetime.
Further tests are needed before human trials begin, which will take several years, but Professor Ronald Crystal of Wale Cornell Medical College in New York said the first results are encouraging.
“We are very hopeful that this vaccine strategy can finally help the millions of smokers who have tried to quit by trying all the methods available on the market today, but have found that their nicotine addiction is strong enough to overcome it with these modern remedies,” said Professor Cornell.
The new vaccine contains a harmless virus that was designed to carry genetic information to produce anti-nicotine antibodies.
The virus selectively infects liver cells, which then begin to produce a stable flow of antibodies.
The antibodies track any nicotine molecules in the blood, neutralizing them before they reach the brain, preventing the smoker from getting a nicotine blow.
In the tests, the vaccinated mice, who were subsequently given nicotine, continued their normal activities.
And mice who were not given the vaccine were relaxing, and this is a sign that nicotine has reached their brains, the researchers say.
These experiments are described in the journal Science Translational Medicine.
Previous tobacco vaccines failed because they contained antibodies.
In order to maintain high levels of antibodies, injections had to be done so often that they turned out to be expensive and impractical.
But the cost of a new vaccine is likely to be much lower because it turns liver cells into antibody factories.
Professor Crystal said that if a future human vaccine were completely safe, it could be given to children before they have the desire to try a cigarette, preventing nicotine addiction.
But more likely it will be used by smokers to quit smoking.
“They’ll know that if they start smoking again, they won’t get that pleasure because of the nicotine vaccine, and it can help them get rid of that habit,” he said.
