Lombard owners in Singapore are doing well while the middle class is struggling.
In a lombard at the Bendemir shopping center in Singapore, Janani Amirthalinga puts a golden bracelet, ring and eyebrows to pay for her daughter’s schooling.
“My husband and I just bought a house, so all my money is invested there,” says Mrs. Amirthalinga.
Although she earns $3,000 ($2,400) a month as an administrator and her husband is also working, the family’s monthly income is not enough, she says.
Indeed, demand in different parts of Southeast Asia – where household debt is growing – is such that ValueMax, where it is conducting its deal, this week became the third lombard listed on the Singapore Stock Exchange.
A jewelry mortgage loan is not just a quick way to get money ($1,300 in the case of Mrs. Amirthaling), but it is almost as cheap as unsecured bank loans.
Typically, Lombards in Singapore charge an effective annual interest rate of 17% — slightly above the 15.4% offered by the United Overseas Bank, a local lender with a branch in the same shopping center.
However, Lombards have the advantage that they do not require a credit check or proof of salary and can issue loans faster than banks.
That’s why millions of people across the region are turning to lombards as families feel pressured by rising cost of living and rapidly rising household debt and consumer debt.
After five years of steady growth following the global financial crisis and cheap loans fuelled by free monetary policy in developed economies, low- and middle-income families are turning to lombards to offset the decline in income as their economies slow down.
This week, Standard & Poor's, a rating agency, pointed to an increase in family lending, mainly due to the growth of mortgages, as a risk factor for the creditworthiness of Asian banks.
Malaysia, Thailand and Singapore had the highest ratio of household debt to gross domestic product in Asia.
Malaysia topped this list with 80 percent of GDP compared to 60 percent in 2008.
Economists are also concerned about the high level of consumer debt in Thailand, which barely got out of a technical recession this week.
On Thursday, data showed a continued decline in exports and a weakening consumer demand.
“The point is that as prices rise, people in the middle and bottom [income scale] will be looking for ways to replenish their income wherever they can,” says Song Seng Wung, an economist at CIMB, a Malaysian bank.
The record high gold prices in the last two years have intensified the rush with which people put their personal belongings as they take advantage of the opportunity to get money for their family jewelry.
In Singapore, about 70% of the things that are laid in the city-state's 200 lombard points are gold products.
People say, “The price of gold looks good, let’s put a grandmother’s gold chain and get it back next month.”
In Thailand, the largest lombard operator EasyMoney has seen a 20% increase in the number of customers using its branches in recent months.
The growth in the lombard business is such that ValueMax, which operates a branch in Bendemira and 15 other in Singapore, plans to expand not only in neighboring Malaysia, where it has four stores, but beyond Asia as well, says Yehah Lee Ching, ValueMax CEO.
The company will fund the expansion using 60 percent of the S$66 million raised this week as a result of a listing on the Singapore Stock Exchange.
While some lenders have caused fire of criticism over the high interest rates, Ms. Yeah says the Lombard not only offers cheaper rates than other lenders, it also does not increase debt directly.
“Customers place items they already own, and monetizing personal assets does not increase household debt,” she says.
The institution is gaining increasingly widespread public recognition as a means of obtaining short-term, secure funding.
And at the same time, lombards are not only used by those categories of people who are in a difficult financial situation.
Wealthy people in Singapore also use ValueMax branches to deposit gold clocks or Rolex watches, which can give up to 60 percent of their purchase value in cash.
We see customers from all walks of life.
“These include wealthy individuals who need to borrow money for a short term for commercial projects or investments, or small business who need to overcome temporary monetary difficulties,” Ms. Yeah says.
Sometimes they just need money very quickly.
