Passengers should turn off their devices again when the aircraft descends for landing and do not turn them on until the aircraft is on the ground.
In accordance with the new guidelines, airlines whose aircraft are adequately protected from electronic interference may allow passengers to use these devices during takeoff, landing and steering, FAO said.
Most new aircraft and other aircraft modified to allow passengers to use Wi-Fi at high altitudes are expected to meet these criteria.
Laura Gleeding, president of the Association of Professional Boat Crews, welcomed the changes.
“Once the new policy is successfully implemented (and we are going to work closely with the carrier to this), it will be a non-performing option,” Gliding said.
We’re frankly tired of feeling “school duty” when it comes to this issue.
But connecting to the internet for surfing, emailing, texting, or downloading data will still be banned at an altitude of less than 10,000 feet, the agency said.
Passengers will be asked to switch their smartphones, tablets and other devices to airplane mode.
Thus, there is still no "Words with Friends" — an intelligent internet game that actor Alec Baldwin played on his smartphone in 2011 when a rumored incident occurred: the actor was removed from an American Airlines aircraft for refusing to turn off the device while the aircraft was near the landing.
And heavier devices, such as laptops, will still need to be placed in the luggage compartment, as they can injure someone if they fly around the cabin.
Calling from mobile phones during the flight will also be prohibited.
Regulatory authority on telephone calls belongs to the Federal Communications Commission, not the FAU.
FAO may lift ban on certain electronic devices during take-off and landing
Last month, Mark Rosenker of the National Transportation Safety Council, a national transportation safety expert at CBS News, said cell phones were still considered a risk.
“Cell phones are really a problem, not only because they can potentially interfere with navigation devices, but we know thanks to the FCC that they can interfere with cellular communications whilst the aircraft is in the air,” Rosenker said.
The industry advisory committee set up by the FAU to study this issue recommended last month that the government allow for more widespread use of personal electronic devices.
In recent years, there has been increasing pressure on FAUs to ease restrictions on their use.
Critics, such as Missouri Democratic Senator Claire McCaskill, say there are no valid reasons for the ban.
Compliance with restrictions is also becoming increasingly difficult to ensure as the use of devices has become ubiquitous.
Some studies show that up to a third of passengers forget or ignore instructions to turn off their devices.
The FAA began to restrict the use of electronic devices by passengers in 1966 in response to reports of interference to navigation and communication equipment, when passengers began to carry FM radio receivers — the high-tech gadgets of the time.
New aircraft are far more dependent on electrical systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also developed and approved by the FAO as resistant to electronic interference.
Airlines have been offering passengers Wi-Fi on cruise altitude for several years.
Airplanes modified for Wi-Fi systems are also more resistant to interference.
The vast majority of launches are adapted for wider use of electronic devices according to the new guidelines, Wertha said.
Today’s electronic devices generally emit radio signals of much lower power than previous generations of devices.
E-book readers, for example, emit only minimal signals when browsing pages.
But the signals become more powerful when devices load or send data.
Among those who sought to ease the restrictions on the use of electronic devices by passengers was the company Amazon.com.
In 2011, the company’s representatives loaded an entire airliner with their Kindle e-book reader and flew on it to check for problems, but never found them.
Members of the FAO Advisory Committee expressed mixed feelings about whether the use of devices poses any risk.
Douglas Kidd of the National Air Passenger Association said he believes the interference from the devices is real, even if the risk is minimal.
Other members of the committee said there were only individual reports from pilots confirming that the devices could interfere with aircraft systems, and most of these reports are very old.
Nevertheless, the committee recommended that the FAA allow pilots to require passengers to turn off devices during instrument landings in conditions of limited visibility.
A group of tourism industry representatives welcomed these changes, calling them a sensible step towards passengers who are now using a variety of technological devices.
“We are pleased that the FAA recognizes that passenger comfort is not incompatible with safety and protection,” said Roger Dow, CEO of the U.S. Tourism Association.
