They measured the heart rate of the animals and analyzed their behavior.
We’ll probably soon understand why their tails sometimes turn in one direction and sometimes in the other.
Professor Valortigara said, “We showed dogs videos – either naturalistic versions or a silhouette – to get rid of any other distortions, and we could manipulate the tail movement and direct the tail more to the left or right.”
When the animals saw that the nothing-expressing dog moved its tail to the right (from the point of view of the dog whistling with its tail), they remained completely relaxed.
But when they noticed that the tail was mostly inclined to the left (again from the sight of the dog whistling with the tail), their heartbeat was accelerating and they looked alarmed.
Professor Valortigara said he doesn’t think the dogs intentionally communicated with each other through these movements.
In fact, he believes that dogs have learned from their experience which movements they should worry about and which ones do not.
He notes, “If there are several encounters with other dogs and frequently twisting their tail in one direction is associated with more friendly behavior, and the right side gives less friendly behavior, then the dog reacts based on that experience.”
Researchers say these findings can give owners, veterinarians and trainers a deeper understanding of their animal’s emotions.
Dog behavior expert John Bradshaw, a guest researcher at the University of Bristol Veterinary School, said this was not the first study to test whether the left and right sides matter for dogs.
Last year, a team of scientists from Lincoln University found that dogs turn their heads to the left when looking at an aggressive dog, and to the right when looking at a happy dog.
And in another research paper at the University of Victoria in Canada, he: “Dogs were more likely to approach a robot dog when the tail of its tail was directed to the left rather than to the right, instead of becoming anxious – the opposite behavior of the Italian study.”
He said the differences could be due to the fact that dogs in various studies did not fully perceive animals in movies or robot dogs as dogs.
It could be useful to study how dogs react to real dogs, he explained.
"While there is sufficient evidence on different mammals that the two hemispheres of the brain are used for different purposes, many details are still to be clarified, and dogs are no exception," he said.
However, given the ease with which their behavior can be recorded, we will probably soon understand why their tails sometimes turn in one direction and sometimes in the other.
