The shout of despair of Obama's voter
I voted for President Obama twice, sharing the hope of change.
He says Obama has allowed Republican obstructionism to overthrow praiseful efforts.
Obstructionism cannot justify problems with the website of the Obama-reformed healthcare system, drone attacks
The memoirs of the 2008 Obama campaign are a sad reminder of what could have been
Nathanie P. Morris is a second-year student at Harvard Medical School.
I’m reading a very sad book these days.
I thought this book would inspire me in the times of disappointment at the second grade of medical school and reawaken in me a sense of hope.
It’s called “Dare to Win,” and it’s memoirs about Barack Obama’s 2008 presidential campaign.
When I finish writing reports on my patients in the evening and go to bed, this book brings me back to a time when politics inspired millions of people, and speeches could have captured the spirit.
The election victory turned out to be impressive, and the head of news programs took a break to understand this historic moment.
My classmates wept of joy, and my parents kept every newspaper they could find.
A young team of strategists had to come to the White House, and the people were ready for change.
When Obama took office in 2008, he was supported by 82 percent.
Then I close the book.
Return to the present is a rough awakening, like pulling out of a dream.
It’s hard to remember those days of optimism – they seem like a distant memory, a sad reminder of missed opportunities.
Over the years since I dropped my first ballot, changes have really happened.
It was something I could not even imagine.
I pay tribute to Obama for his great and varied achievements, from the adoption of the law on affordable medical care to the withdrawal of our troops from Iraq, the abolition of the “don’t ask, don’t say” rule, and the assassination of Osama bin Laden.
Moreover, I believe that party obstructionism has blocked too many attempts to advance our country: immigration reform, the possibility of choosing public healthcare, and the closure of a base in Guantanamo, among others.
But after countless times I have been on the side of the Obama administration, defending it from colleagues and peers, I have exhausted the explanations I can provide.
I have reached the point of political despair.
Republican obstructionism cannot explain permission to listen to foreign leaders or to attack innocent children in other countries by drones.
He cannot explain the National Security Agency’s gathering of data on the privacy of Americans or the prosecution of exponents exposing government illicit actions.
He cannot explain the murder of U.S. citizen Anvar al-Avlaki without trial and investigation, or the non-compliance with public funding and spending limits during the presidential campaign.
He can’t justify the report’s findings that the White House’s efforts to silence the media are “the most aggressive ... since the Nixon administration.”
And lately, he can’t justify not being able to develop a simple website for more than three years after the Accessible Healthcare Act was signed.
I don’t know if I should have expected that.
Should I have understood at the age of 18 that the leadership could contradict the political campaigns that preceded it?
Obviously, working for an elected post is not a predictable program of action, as our public dialogue will be shaped by an opposition political party and by random events such as the Newtown beat.
Nevertheless, from all the examples I listed above, it is clear that they were largely the administration’s own choice.
And that is what worries me the most.
I voted for Obama again in 2012, but not because I was enthusiastic about his candidacy.
Mitt Romney was an incomprehensible and rude alternative, seeming incapable of deciding on his own policies or views.
I believed that in his second term, Obama, freeing himself from the pressure of the upcoming elections, would justify the hopes we have heard of for so long.
However, when Obama’s rating dropped below 45 percent this week, it became much harder to go back to 2008 through this book.
This makes me grieve for many promises that have been failed.
This week I read the part of the book that describes how Clinton defeated Obama in the Pennsylvania primary elections.
At a meeting to analyze the causes of the failure, he told his staff that they should return to normal and remain true to their goal.
“I want us to get our attractiveness back,” he said.
We need to remember who we are.”
Five years have passed, Mr. President, and I totally agree with you.
The opinions expressed in this comment belong exclusively to Nathan Morris.
