For 21 years, Georges Bouvelle saw his father come back to life and again fall unconscious, wandering through hospitals that were not properly equipped to help him.
Jamef Bwelle was injured in a car accident in 1981 near Jaunda, the capital of Cameroon.
At first, he had only a broken arm, but the resulting infection spread to the brain and caused a hematoma that reminded him of himself for the rest of his life.
“There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon,” Georges Buelle said.
If we had the money, we would have taken it out of Cameroon.
Instead, Bwell accompanied his father for years in crowded clinics and hospitals, receiving any treatment they could get.
“It’s not easy,” said Bowie.
“You can leave home at 5 a.m., run to the hospital to be the first, but you’re not the first.
A lot of patients.
Some may die because of what they have to wait for.
The situation hasn’t changed much since Father Bwell died in 2002.
According to the World Health Organization, there is only one doctor per 5,000 people in Cameroon.
For comparison, the ratio in the United States is one doctor per 413 people.
And even if Cameroons could go to a doctor, many of them would not be in their pocket.
Two out of five people in this country live below the poverty line, and three-quarters of healthcare spending in it is private.
“Their only problem is poverty,” Bwell said.
And because of poverty, they can’t enjoy their lives.”
Seeing the suffering of his father and many of his countrymen, Bwell was determined to do something about it.
Last year, Dr. Georges Bovelle and his team of volunteers performed 700 free surgeries.
He himself became a physician and works as a vascular surgeon at the Younde Central Hospital.
He also founded the non-profit organization ASCOVIME, which organizes trips to the countryside on weekends to provide free medical care.
Since 2008, he and his group of volunteers have helped 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, he and up to 30 other people are loaded in vans, attaching medical supplies to the roofs and traveling through the crossroads to visit the village in need.
They are not always accompanied by luck.
Several times they had to push cars through rivers and dirt.
But when they come, they are met as real heroes: it is a celebration with songs and dances and the best rooms that locals can offer.
Free medical care in these villages is indeed a reason to celebrate, and Bwell with his wide smile and boundless energy is more than happy to join the fun.
The next morning, the brigade begins to receive hundreds of patients.
“We accept 500 people on each trip,” Bwell said.
They come from all over the district within a radius of 60 kilometers from the village, and they come on foot.
Each of these weekend clinics provides a variety of medical services.
Many people are treated for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others may get coffins, donated points, or free birth certificates—documents required for school that many poor families simply can’t afford.
In the evening, the brigade performs simple operations under local anesthesia.
Operations are usually carried out in a school, municipality or home building; after the procedure, patients get up and go to the postoperative area to free up space for the next person.
Using a generator to illuminate operational and sanitary handling equipment, Bwell and his volunteers work until early Sunday morning.
It’s a hard pace, but the brigade’s dedication usually helps support the country musicians.
“They beat the drums all night to keep us awake and continue to work,” Bwell said.
On Sunday, the members of the brigade go back to the city, tired but proud of their work.
This team, consisting of Cameroonian doctors and international medical students, conducted 700 free operations over the past year, and they know that their help can be of tremendous importance to those they are helping.
One person explained that the free surgery he received to treat his hernia would allow him to work again.
“It will change the future for me and my family,” the man said.
In addition to these clinical treatments on weekends and hospital work, the surgeon Bwell also works at night in private medical clinics around Jaunde.
This second work, he said, provides 60% of the funding of his non-profit organization; the rest of the funds are covered by private donations.
“I don’t even know when he’s asleep,” said Katie O’Malley, a doctoral student at Drake’s University in Philadelphia, a volunteer in the Bowl.
He’s always either in the hospital or trying to make money for the organization to continue these campaigns.
For future doctors and nurses such as O’Malley, coming from the U.S. and Europe to join Bewell in his tasks, it’s an opportunity to practice that they’d never got at home.
“We were given the opportunity to assist in surgeries where we helped remove blood spots or hold instruments for Dr. Bowelle,” O’Malley said.
As a secondary student, you would never get such an opportunity in America.
Volunteer students usually pay for their trip to Cameroon themselves, often arriving with donated medicines.
But upon arrival in Jaunda, their food, transport and training is paid by Bwell.
“He’s a hero, no doubt,” O’Malley said.
He gives his life to this organization, and his desire to help the people of Cameroon is endless.
For Bwell, being almost constantly busy with work is not a tough test.
Helping others to live a happy life, fulfilling the promise given to his father is what brings him great joy.
“I’m so happy when I do this job,” Bowelle said.
I think of my father.
I hope he sees what I am doing.
I do this to make people laugh to reduce their pain.
