Australian woman appeals against prison sentence in Thailand
A 21-year-old woman from Sydney, sentenced to 15 days in prison on Phuket Island for false claims that she was attacked by a taxi driver, appealed the sentence and was released on bail.
Stevie Roselle Bumford was initially found guilty by the Phuket Provincial Court on June 15 for filing a false lawsuit after Thailand’s police that a local taxi driver had carried out the assault on Sunday night, June 10, while two other men held her.
However, video surveillance cameras later revealed that she returned safely to her hotel after breaking up with her Australian boyfriend.
Phuket police questioned Bumford for two days before admitting that they had fabricated the story.
Before the trial she was detained in local police chambers.
Bumford was sentenced to a 15-day prison sentence in a general regime prisoner detention center on the outskirts of Phuket, rather than a female adult prison.
She is the daughter of former Australian league player Peter Tanks, who appealed to the Canberra Foreign Ministry for help for his daughter.
Tanks told the Sydney Sunday Telegraph that the whole family was “extremely concerned” about their daughter’s well-being and was waiting for her to return to Australia.
"Obviously, it was an alarming time, but we hope she will return home safely as soon as possible," Tanks said.
Bumford appealed her sentence and was released on bail of 50,000 baht.
According to reports in Australia, she is currently spending her vacation in the resort area of Krabi in southern Thailand.
Legal sources in Thailand that Bumford is currently serving as a local lawyer in Phuket, but warned that the appeal could lead to the court extending her sentence to two years and forcing her to serve a term in adult prison.
However, after the recent murder of Australian travel agent Michelle Smith in Phuket, Thailand may also seek to restore its undermined tourist image, leading to an acquittal sentence.
